title: fatal: out of memory on raspberry pi 3
body:
#### System information

**Geth version:** 

Geth
Version: 1.7.0-stable
Git Commit: 6c6c7b2af3efdad4d2f64f70f3a724af434bbcd2
Architecture: arm
Protocol Versions: [63 62] 
Network Id: 1
Go Version: go1.7.4
Operating System: linux
GOPATH=
GOROOT=/usr/local/go

**OS & Version:** 

Linux rpi3 4.9.35-v7+ #1014 SMP Fri Jun 30 14:47:43 BST 2017 armv7l GNU/Linux

**Commit hash : (if `develop`)**

**#### Expected behaviour**

Full sync, normally operating system

**#### Actual behaviour**

Syncs for a while (crash at ~50%, at increasing frequency and now all the time at ~86%) then system seems to run out of memory which locks up the entire system. Eventually geth gets killed after a few minutes by OOM killer and system recovers.

**#### Steps to reproduce the behaviour**

`nice -n 19 ionice -c2 -n7 /geth-linux-arm7-1.7.0-6c6c7b2a/geth --datadir /ethData --syncmode fast 2>> /ethData/geth.log`

**#### Backtrace**

````
Killed
````

syslog:

Sep 21 13:35:21 rpi3 kernel: [4128757.492106] Out of memory: Kill process 18089 (geth) score 810 or sacrifice child
Sep 21 13:35:21 rpi3 kernel: [4128757.492195] Killed process 18089 (geth) total-vm:1657260kB, anon-rss:834964kB, file-rss:0kB, shmem-rss:0kB
Sep 21 13:35:21 rpi3 kernel: [4128757.722217] oom_reaper: reaped process 18089 (geth), now anon-rss:0kB, file-rss:0kB, shmem-rss:0kB

Is there not enough memory on a Raspberry Pi 3 to run a node now?

Around ~86% syncing (block: 3852904), geth uses ~835MB of memory.

Turning on swap resolves the OOM killer but drastically reduces sync speed. 

Other options are:  reduce the amount of memory available to the GPU on the RPi3, freeing up more memory Or use a SBC with more RAM.

As the size of the block chain increases, this will become more problematic for low power nodes. 

Curious to know why geth needs so much memory? Does it have to store all hashes in memory?
Is it possible to limit the amount of memory used and complete the operation in chunks?
